Disk Forensics > [T6]: Windows LNK Files: Analysis and Attributes

(4) LNK Files

An LNK file is a Windows shortcut, a pointer to open a file or folder. It holds forensically valuable information about the original file it points to, such as creation date, size, location...etc. LNK files can be created automatically by the operating system when a user opens a file or manually, using the right-click create shortcut option. The operating system uses LNK files to support launching applications, linking, and storing application references to a target file.


LNK files can be found in multiple places on the system. The best way to collect them is to capture a triage image for *.LNK, which will grab every LNK file in the selected path. However, most LNK files exist at the following locations:

  1. C:\Users\<User>\Appdata\Roaming\Microsoft\Windows\Recent
  2. C:\Users\<User>\Desktop
  3. C:\Users\<User>\AppData\Roaming\Microsoft\Office\Recent\ 
  4. C:\Users\<User>\Downloads

Taking the "triage image" route, we will use Kape to create a triage image to collect LNK files, parse them using LECmd and prepare it to be analysis-ready using "Timeline Explorer"


Looking at the first part of the output (parsed) file, we can see the following details.

Parsed LNK files opened using Timeline Explorer (part 1)

  • Columns 1-4 include source file (.lnk) details.
  • Columns 5-9 include the details of the target file (the actual file that the .lnk file points to).

 

The second part includes additional information.

Parsed LNK files opened using Timeline Explorer (part 2)

  1. File attributes (e.g., hidden, system, read-only..etc.).
  2. The volume serial number is the serial number of the partition hosting this file. This is very helpful in identifying external drives involved in the case.
  3. Type of the drive where the file resides (Removable or fixed).
  4. Volume label.
  5. File path.
  6. Hostname
  7. The system MAC address.
